The limit of a Function¶

It appears that we can make the values of $f(x)$ as close as we like to $4$ by taking $x$ sufficiently close to 2. We express this by saying the limit of the function as approaches 2 is equal to 4.

Notation:

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to 2} (x^2-x+2) = 4 \end{equation}

Definition

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = L \end{equation}

Means that we can make the values of $f(x)$ arbitrarily close to $L$ (as close to $L$ as we like) by taking $x$ to be sufficiently close to $a$ (on either side of $a$) but not equal to $a$.

  • In finding the limit of $ f(x) $ as $x$ approaches $a$, we never consider $x=a$.
  • In fact, $ f(x) $ need not even be defined when $x=a$.
  • The only thing that matters is how it is defined near $a$.

In each case, regardless of what happens at $a$, it is true that $ \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = L$.

Example: Guess the value of

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to 1} \frac{x-1}{x^2-1} \end{equation}

What is the limit of $ f(x)=\left\lbrace \begin{array}{ll} \frac{x-1}{x^2-1}, ~~ if x\ne 1 \\ 2,~~ x = 1 \end{array} \right. $ ?

In both cases, $\lim_{x\to 1} f(x)=0.5$

Example: Estimate the value of

\begin{equation} \lim_{t\to 0} \frac{\sqrt{t^2+9}-3}{t^2} \end{equation}

It seems to be $1/6$

If we try with even smaller values ...

Definition of Limit¶

To motivate the precise definition of a limit, lets consider the function

\begin{equation} f(x)=\left\lbrace \begin{array}{ll} 2x-1, ~~ if x\ne 3 \\ 6,~~ x = 3 \end{array} \right. \end{equation}

Intuitively, $\lim_{x\to 3} f(x) = 5$

  • Such phrases as $x$ is close to $3$ and $f(x)$ gets closer and closer to $5$ are vague.
  • We ask instead, How close to $3$ does $x$ have to be so that $f(x)$ differs from $5$ by less than $0.l$?
  • So, our problem is to find a number $\delta$ such that:
\begin{equation} |f(x)-5| < 0.1 ~~~ if ~~~ |x-3| < \delta ~~~ but ~x\ne3 \end{equation}
\begin{equation} |f(x)-5| < 0.1 \Rightarrow |2x-1-5| < 0.1 \end{equation}
\begin{equation} \Rightarrow |2x-6| < 0.1 \Rightarrow |2(x-3)| < 0.1 \end{equation}
\begin{equation} \Rightarrow |x-3| < 0.005 \end{equation}

That is,

\begin{equation} |f(x)-5| < 0.1 ~~~ if ~~~ 0< |x-3| < 0.005 \end{equation}

In a simmilar way:

\begin{equation} |f(x)-5| < 0.01 ~~~ if ~~~ 0< |x-3| < 0.0005 \end{equation}\begin{equation} |f(x)-5| < 0.001 ~~~ if ~~~ 0< |x-3| < 0.00005 \end{equation}

For 5 to be the precise limit of $f(x)$ as $x$ approaches 3, we must not only be able to bring the difference between $f(x)$ and $5$ below each of these three numbers; we must be able to bring it below any positive number.

By the same reasoning:

\begin{equation} |f(x)-5| < \epsilon ~~~ if ~~~ 0< |x-3| < \delta = \frac{\epsilon}{2} \end{equation}

Or...

\begin{equation} if ~~~ 3-\delta < x < 3 + \delta ~~~ (x \ne 3) ~~~~~~ then ~~~~~~ 5-\epsilon < f(x) < 5 + \epsilon \end{equation}

Precise definition of a limit¶

Let $f$ be a function defined on some open interval that contains the number $a$, except possibly at $a$ itself. Then we say that the limit of $f(x)$ as $x$ approaches $a$ is $L$, and we write

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = L \end{equation}

if for every number $\epsilon > 0$ there is a number $\delta > 0$ such that

\begin{equation} if ~~~ 0< |x-a| < \delta ,~~~ then ~~~ |f(x)-L| < \epsilon \end{equation}

Another way to say the same thing is:

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = L \Leftrightarrow \forall ~~~ \epsilon > 0 ~~~ \exists \delta >0 / |x-a|<\delta \Rightarrow |f(x)-L|<\epsilon \end{equation}

Left-hand limit¶

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a^-} f(x) = L \Leftrightarrow \forall ~~~ \epsilon > 0 ~~~ \exists ~~ \delta >0 ~/ ~a-\delta <x<a \Rightarrow |f(x)-L|<\epsilon \end{equation}

Right-hand limit¶

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a^+} f(x) = L \Leftrightarrow \forall ~~~ \epsilon > 0 ~~~ \exists ~~ \delta >0 ~/ ~a<x<a+\delta \Rightarrow |f(x)-L|<\epsilon \end{equation}

Theorem: Existence of a limit¶

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = L \Leftrightarrow \lim_{x\to a^-} f(x) = \lim_{x\to a^+} f(x)=L ~~~ \& ~~~ it~ is~ UNIQUE \end{equation}

Example:

Calculate

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to 1} \frac{2x}{x-3}=\frac{2}{1-3}=-1 \end{equation}

Definition¶

Let $f$ be defined on both sides of $a$, except possibly at $a$ itself. Then

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = +\infty \end{equation}

means that the values of $f(x)$ can be made arbitrarily large positive by taking $x$ sufficiently close to $a$, but not equal to $a$.

That is,

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = +\infty \Leftrightarrow \forall ~~~ M > 0 ~~~ \exists ~~ \delta >0 ~\big/ ~0<|x-a|<\delta \Rightarrow f(x)>M \end{equation}

Definition¶

Let $f$ be defined on both sides of $a$, except possibly at $a$ itself. Then

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = -\infty \end{equation}

means that the values of $f(x)$ can be made arbitrarily large negative by taking $x$ sufficiently close to $a$, but not equal to $a$.

That is,

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = -\infty \Leftrightarrow \forall ~~~ N < 0 ~~~ \exists ~~ \delta >0 ~\big / ~0<|x-a|<\delta \Rightarrow f(x)<N \end{equation}

Similar definitions can be given for the one-sided infinite limits.

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a^-} f(x) = \infty ~~~~~~ \lim_{x\to a^+} f(x) = \infty \end{equation}\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a^-} f(x) = -\infty ~~~~~~ \lim_{x\to a^+} f(x) = -\infty \end{equation}

Definition¶

The line $x=a$ is called a vertical asymptote of the curve $y=f(x)$ if at least one of the following statements is true:

Examples

  • $\lim_{x\to 0^+} \ln x = -\infty $
  • $\lim_{x\to \pi/2^-} \tan x= \infty $
  • $\lim_{x\to \pi/2^+} \tan x= -\infty $

Definition¶

Let $f$ be defined on some interval $(a,\infty)$. Then

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to \infty} f(x) = L \end{equation}

means that the values of $f(x)$ can be made arbitrarily close to $L$ by taking $x$ sufficiently large positive.

That is,

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to \infty} f(x) = L \Leftrightarrow \forall ~~~ \epsilon > 0 ~~~ \exists ~~ M>0 ~\big / x>M \Rightarrow |f(x)-L|<\epsilon \end{equation}

Definition¶

Let $f$ be defined on some interval $(-\infty,a)$. Then

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to -\infty} f(x) = L \end{equation}

means that the values of $f(x)$ can be made arbitrarily close to $L$ by taking $x$ sufficiently large negative.

That is,

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to -\infty} f(x) = L \Leftrightarrow \forall ~~~ \epsilon > 0 ~~~ \exists ~~ M<0 ~\big / x<M \Rightarrow |f(x)-L|<\epsilon \end{equation}

Definition¶

The line $y=L$ is called a horizontal asymptote of the curve $y=f(x)$ if either

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to \infty} f(x) = L ~~~~ or ~~~~ \lim_{x\to -\infty} f(x) = L \end{equation}

Limits Laws¶

Suppose that $c$ is a constant and the limits below exist

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a} f(x) ~~~ and ~~~ \lim_{x\to a} g(x) \end{equation}

Then,

  1. $\lim_{x\to a} [f(x)+g(x)]=\lim_{x\to a} f(x)+\lim_{x\to a} g(x) $
  1. $\lim_{x\to a} [f(x)-g(x)]=\lim_{x\to a} f(x)-\lim_{x\to a} g(x) $
  1. $\lim_{x\to a} [cf(x)]=c\lim_{x\to a} f(x) $
  1. $\lim_{x\to a} [f(x)\cdot g(x)]=\lim_{x\to a} f(x)\cdot\lim_{x\to a} g(x) $
  1. $\lim_{x\to a} [f(x)/ g(x)]=\lim_{x\to a} f(x)/\lim_{x\to a} g(x) $ if $\lim_{x\to a} g(x) \ne 0$

Exercise 2

b. $\lim_{x\to 1} [f(x)\cdot g(x)]$

c. $\lim_{x\to 2} [f(x)/g(x)]$

More laws...

  1. $\lim_{x\to a} [f(x)^n]=\big[\lim_{x\to a} f(x)\big]^n $, $n=1,2,3,...$
  1. $\lim_{x\to a} c=c $
  1. $\lim_{x\to a} x=a $
  1. $\lim_{x\to a} [x^n]=a^n $
  1. $\lim_{x\to a} \sqrt[n]{x}=\sqrt[n]{a}$, if $n$ is even $a\ge0$
  1. $\lim_{x\to a} \sqrt[n]{f(x)}=\sqrt[n]{\lim_{x\to a} f(x)}$, if $n$ is even $\lim_{x\to a} f(x)\ge0$
  1. $\lim_{x\to a} \ln \big( f(x) \big)=\ln\big(\lim_{x\to a} f(x)\big)$, $\lim_{x\to a} f(x)>0$
  1. $\lim_{x\to a} \sin \big( f(x) \big)=\sin\big(\lim_{x\to a} f(x)\big)$

Direct substitution property¶

If $f$ is a polynomial or a rational function and $a$ is in the domain of $f$, then

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = f(a) \end{equation}

Example

Find

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to\infty} \frac{1}{x} ~~ and ~~ \lim_{x\to-\infty} \frac{1}{x} \end{equation}

When $x$ is large, $1/ x$ is small. For instance,

\begin{equation} \frac{1}{100} = 0.01 ~~~ \frac{1}{10,000} = 0.0001 ~~~ \frac{1}{1,000,000} = 0.000001 \end{equation}

In fact, by taking $x$ large enough, we can make $f(x)$ as close to $0$ as we please.

\begin{equation} \frac{1}{x} < \epsilon \Rightarrow x > \frac{1}{\epsilon}=M \end{equation}

Therefore, we can make $1/x$ arbitrarily close to $0$ by taking $x$ suficiently large. We can conclude that,

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to\infty} \frac{1}{x}=0 \end{equation}

Theorem¶

If $r>0$ is a rational number, then

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to\infty} \frac{1}{x^r}=0 \end{equation}

If $r>0$ is a rational number such that $x^r$ is defined for all $x$, then

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to-\infty} \frac{1}{x^r}=0 \end{equation}

Theorem¶

If $f(x)\le g(x)$ when $x$ is near $a$ (except possibly at $a$) and the limits of $f$ and $g$ both exist as approaches $a$, then

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a} f(x)\le\lim_{x\to a} g(x) \end{equation}

THE SQUEEZE THEOREM¶

If $f(x)\le g(x)\le h(x)$ when $x$ is near $a$ (except possibly at $a$) and

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a} f(x)=\lim_{x\to a} h(x)=L \end{equation}

then

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a} g(x)=L \end{equation}

Indeterminations¶

\begin{equation} \frac{0}{0},~~~ \frac{\infty}{\infty},~~~ \infty-\infty,~~~ 1^\infty,~~~ \infty^0,~~ 0^0 \end{equation}
  1. $\frac{0}{0}\rightarrow$ simplify
  1. $\frac{\infty}{\infty}\rightarrow$ comparison, $x^x>a^x>x^a>\log_a x$
  1. $\infty-\infty \rightarrow $ convert into a $\frac{0}{0}$ or $\frac{\infty}{\infty}$

Review¶

Special Limit¶

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to 0} \frac{\sin x}{x}=1 \end{equation}

Proof:

From (b)

$arclenght=radius\cdot\theta(rad) $ $\Rightarrow ~ arc ~AB=1\cdot \theta$

From (a)

$BC<AB<arc~AB$ and $BC=\sin\theta$

\begin{equation}\Rightarrow sin\theta<\theta\end{equation}
\begin{equation} or~~~ \frac{sin\theta}{\theta}<1 \end{equation}

On the other hand,

\begin{equation} \tan \theta = \frac{AD}{AO}=\frac{AD}{1}>\theta \end{equation}
\begin{equation} \Rightarrow \frac{\sin \theta}{\cos \theta} >\theta \Rightarrow \cos \theta < \frac{\sin \theta}{\theta} \end{equation}

then ...

\begin{equation} \cos \theta < \frac{\sin \theta}{\theta} < 1 \end{equation}

taking limits $\theta \rightarrow 0$

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to 0} \cos \theta < \lim_{x\to 0} \frac{\sin \theta}{\theta} < \lim_{x\to 0} 1 \end{equation}\begin{equation} \Rightarrow 1 < \lim_{x\to 0} \frac{\sin \theta}{\theta} < 1 \end{equation}\begin{equation} \Rightarrow \lim_{x\to 0} \frac{\sin \theta}{\theta} =1 \end{equation}

Some useful approximations¶

  • if $f(x)\rightarrow 0\Rightarrow \sin\big(f(x)\big)\approx f(x)$ $\Rightarrow \sin \approx$ line close to the origin

  • if $f(x)\rightarrow 0\Rightarrow \cos\big(f(x)\big)\approx 1- \big[f(x)\big]^ 2\big/2$ $\Rightarrow \cos \approx$ parabola close to the origin

Limits in $\Re^3$¶

Definition¶

Let $f$ be a function of two variables whose domain $D$ includes points arbitrarily close to (a,b). Then we say that the limit of $f(x,y)$ as $(x,y)$ approaches $(a,b)$ is $L$ and we write

\begin{equation} \lim_{(x,y)\to (a,b)} f(x,y)=L \end{equation}

if for every number $\epsilon>0$ there is a corresponding number $\delta>0$ such that if $(x,y)\in D$ and $\sqrt{(x-a)^2+(y-b)^ 2}<\delta$ then $|f(x,y)-L|<\epsilon$.

  • In $\Re^3$ there are $\infty$ many directions to approach to the limit, not only left and right.
  • If the limit depend on the direction, this is, it depends on $\theta$, it will not exist.
  • The limit exists if
\begin{equation} \lim_{(x,y)\to (a,b)} f(x,y)=\lim_{\rho\to 0~~~ \forall ~ \theta} f(x_0+\rho\cos \theta,y_0+\rho\sin \theta) \end{equation}
